                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On January 6, 1948, at Washington, Major General Donald H. Connolly, the Foreign
                    Liquidation Commissioner, and Vassili C. Dendramis, <pb facs="0028" n="8"
                        xml:id="pg_8"/> the Greek Ambassador, entered into an agreement under which
                    the United States extended to Greece a further line of credit for the purchase
                    of up to $25,000,000 worth of United States surplus property; for text, see
                    United Nations Treaty Series, volume 184, page 258.</p>
                <p>This agreement was the fifth involving sales of surplus property to Greece. For
                    information on the four agreements entered into in 1946 and 1947, which extended
                    credits to Greece totaling $55,000,000, see footnotes 26 and 96, <ref
                        target="frus1946v07#pg_175">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1946, volume VII, pages 175</ref>
                    and <ref target="frus1946v07#pg_232">232</ref>; and editorial note, <ref
                        target="frus1947v05#pg_171">
                        <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1947, volume V, page 171</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
